:false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80165"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man is admitted for urosepsis, which is currently being treated with antibiotics. His creatinine has increased from 100 to 210 umol/L (45-90). An in-dwelling catheter has been in situ for the past four days and is draining urine freely, however he has now developed frank haematuria without clots. Thus, his usual apixaban (for paroxysmal atrial fibrillation) was not given. Today, the patient reports chest pain occurring when he walks around the ward. The pain is central, dull, and heavy, and resolves with rest. He is currently pain-free. His observations are all within normal ranges. An ECG is performed (image 1), which is compared against an old ECG from several years prior (image 2). His serial troponins are 38 and 42. (\u003C30 ng/L).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of his current symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Coronary vasospasm","Stable angina","Unstable angina","ST-elevation myocardial infarction","Non-ST elevation myocardial infarction"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe history is suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Estable angina\u003C/strong\u003E, as the patient\u0027s symptoms occur on exertion and resolve with rest. Adding to his myocardial oxygen demand are his current illnesses, which would lower the exertional threshold for ischaemia to occur. His elevated troponin is more likely to reflect underlying renal impairment rather than myocardial damage, and the increase from one result to the next is insufficient to support ongoing ischaemia (\u003C6ng/L).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn unstable angina and myocardial infarction symptoms occur irrespective of exertional activity, and the latter is associated with concerning troponin elevation. This patient\u0027s ECG shows a left bundle branch block -- if this were a new finding it could raise suspicion of an infarct, but it was also present on the patient\u0027s old ECG. It might be challenging to diagnose infarction in patients with left bundle branch block. To help clinical diagnosis, \u003Cstrong\u003ESgarbossa criteria\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to determine the presence of an infarct in patients with diagnosed left bundle branch block (LBBB). It includes 3 criteria: \u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EST elevation\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003E 1mm\u003C/strong\u003E in leads with a positive QRS complex \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConcordant ST depression\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003E 1 mm\u003C/strong\u003E in leads V1-V3 \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E ST elevation\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003E 5 mm\u003C/strong\u003E in any leads that is discordant with the QRS complex \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most recent ECG of the patient does not feature any of the criteria above, making ongoing ischaemia unlikely. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn coronary vasospasm, patients present with chest pain, most commonly at rest, and may have transient ischaemic ECG changes. However, a first episode of coronary vasospasm is highly unlikely in this age group.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Stable angina onsets with exertion, resolves with rest, and is not associated with ECG changes or troponin elevations","Renal impairment may cause mild persistent troponin elevations","Sgarbossa criteria can be used to determine the presence of an infarct in patients with diagnosed left bundle branch block (LBBB)"],"references":["Wilner, B, de Lemos, JA, Neeland, IJ, 2017, \u2018LBBB in Patients With Suspected MI: An Evolving Paradigm\u2019,\u00a0American College of Cardiology: Latest in Cardiology.","Das D, McGrath BM. Sgarbossa criteria for acute myocardial infarction. CMAJ. 2016 Oct 18;188(15):E395-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65442"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"254"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18272"},{"type":"media","id":"18273"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18272"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/afb91776-adbc-4473-a9c1-13e28fc9bb96.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/afb91776-adbc-4473-a9c1-13e28fc9bb96.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":717}},{"type":"media","id":"18273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18273"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/70a06ce7-6b09-43dc-b57c-330a35d3d667.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/70a06ce7-6b09-43dc-b57c-330a35d3d667.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1435,"height":673}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65442"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-17T22:15:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-17T22:17:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"254"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80165"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"descr